es to visit for a family dinner with her new boyfriend (who turns out to be the psychiatrist she's seeing about her mental illness), but Ken is less than happy to see her with a new man.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 18\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 9\n | Title = The Last Noelle\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2000|12|19}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-10\n | DirectedBy = Jack Kenny\n | WrittenBy = Jennifer Fisher\n | ShortSummary = Christopher attends the funeral of his first girlfriend, Noelle, but things get sticky when Erin discovers that Titus had another love before her and that Titus' first serious girlfriend was as abusive as manipulative as his mother.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 19\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 10\n | Title = Sunday! Sunday! Sunday!\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|1|9}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-09\n | DirectedBy = Robert Berlinger\n | WrittenBy = John R. Morey\n | ShortSummary = At a car show, Titus takes credit for Tommy and Dave's work, leading to a fight that threatens the future of Titus's shop.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 20\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 11\n | Title = When I Say Jump\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|1|16}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-11\n | DirectedBy = Brian Hargrove\n | WrittenBy = Christopher Case\n | ShortSummary = Titus and his friends go bridge-jumping with parachutes to get off on the thrill of excitement. But when Erin protests, Titus realizes that now that he has something to live for, he has second thoughts. Unfortunately, so does Erin.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 21\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 12\n | Title = Episode Twenty-Seven\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|1|30}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-12\n | DirectedBy = [[Joe Regalbuto]]\n | WrittenBy = Sally Lapiduss\n | ShortSummary = Ken asks Christopher to be the best man at his wedding to Kathy. When Kathy pushes Christopher too far at the rehearsal dinner, Christopher retaliates&nbsp;&ndash; by showing her the video from \"What's Up, Hollywood\".\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 22\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 13\n | Title = The Smell of Success\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|2|6}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-13\n | DirectedBy = Jack Kenny\n | WrittenBy = Christopher Titus\n | ShortSummary = After his antics at a national car show are published in ''Street Rodder'' magazine, Christopher finds his shop losing customers and revenue. Things get worse when Ken refuses to help his son and Christopher starts hitting the bottle.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 23\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 14\n | Title = Deprogramming Erin\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|2|13}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-14\n | DirectedBy = [[Gary Shimokawa]]\n | WrittenBy = Chris Sheridan\n | ShortSummary = After losing his shop and his girlfriend, Titus quits drinking and decides to win Erin back, but Erin's dysfunctional family (most of which were last seen in \"The Perfect Thanksgiving\") will not let their daughter go without a fight.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 24\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 15\n | Title = NASCAR\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|2|20}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-15\n | DirectedBy = Jeff Melman\n | WrittenBy = Christopher Case\n | ShortSummary = Erin tricks Christopher into taking his father with him on his trip to North Carolina to deliver a NASCAR stock car.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 25\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 16\n | Title = Life Forward\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|2|27}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-16\n | DirectedBy = Robert Berlinger\n | WrittenBy = Jim Hope\n | ShortSummary = A self-help guru ([[David Hyde-Pierce]]) gets more than he bargained for when the Titus family arrives at his seminar \"Life Forward\".\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 26\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 17\n | Title = Gift of the Car Guy\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|3|13}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-17\n | DirectedBy = Robert Berlinger\n | WrittenBy = Jennifer Fisher\n | ShortSummary = Christopher sells Erin's car without telling her to buy a drag racing funny car to revive his dead car shop, but soon learns that Erin has been working as a strip club waitress to support herself and Titus following the closing of Titus's business.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 27\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 18\n | Title = Tommy's Girlfriend II\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|3|27}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-18\n | DirectedBy = Jeff Melman\n | WrittenBy = Patrick Meighan\n | ShortSummary = Tiffany, the waitress Christopher slept with in \"The Break Up\", begins dating Tommy&nbsp;&ndash; but Christopher thinks the relationship is just a ruse to get closer to him -- and Tiffany reveals her true intentions after getting paralyzed while having sex with a prep cook.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 28\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 19\n | Title = Hard Ass\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|4|10}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-20\n | DirectedBy = Bill Shea\n | WrittenBy = Chris Sheridan\n | ShortSummary = Erin and Titus argue over how to discipline Amy, Erin's wild, destructive teenage niece who was thrown out after beating Erin's brother with a skateboard and has plans to sell marijuana from the garage.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 29\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 20\n | Title = Private Dave\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|4|17}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-21\n | DirectedBy = Gary Shimokawa\n | WrittenBy = Sally Lapiduss\n | ShortSummary = Titus tries to save his brother from committing suicide (after Dave finds a \"Dear John\" letter from his girlfriend, Nancy) at the bus station, but Titus discovers something worse: Dave has enlisted in the Army.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 30\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 21\n | Title = Three Strikes\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|4|24}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-22\n | DirectedBy = Joe Regalbuto\n | WrittenBy = David L. Moses\n | ShortSummary = After coming home to find his house burglarized and his girlfriend laid up on the couch with a broken leg, Titus accuses Erin's degenerate brother, Michael (who will be sent to prison for life under California's \"three strikes\" law) of the crime and has him arrested &nbsp;&ndash; only to regret his decision when the actual burglar returns to the scene of the crime.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 31\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 22\n | Title = The Pit\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|5|8}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-23\n | DirectedBy = [[John Amodeo]]\n | WrittenBy = Robert Hawkins\n | ShortSummary = Part one of two. To get his shop's reputation back, Christopher begins drag racing to get his name back into the car world. After an argument with his father, Christopher ends up clinging to life when his car crashes. <br /> '''Guest Starring''': [[Jay Leno]] as himself\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 32\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 23\n | Title = The Pendulum\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|5|15}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-24\n | DirectedBy = Jack Kenny\n | WrittenBy = Christopher Titus\n | ShortSummary = Conclusion. With Titus in a coma following his accident from \"The Pit\", Ken (who is narrating from the Neutral Space) and Erin must decide whether to let Titus come out of the coma or pull the plug.\n\n''Note'': This episode is dedicated to Christopher Titus's father, Ken (of whom Stacey Keach's character on the show is based).\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 33\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 24\n | Title = The Wedding\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|5|22}}\n | ProdCode = 2ADK-19\n | DirectedBy = Kevin Rodney Sullivan\n | WrittenBy = John R. Morey\n | ShortSummary = While at the church to make preparations for their wedding, Christopher and Erin spontaneously decide to marry avoid having to deal with their dysfunctional families. But when Tommy blows their cover, Titus and Erin struggle to go through with the ceremony until Juanita's abusive psychiatrist boyfriend punches her in the face and Titus and Dave tie him down and try to convince Juanita to dump him.\n | LineColor = EEC433\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 3 (2001\u201302) {{anchor|Season 3}}===\n{{Episode table |background=#03C03C |overall=7 |season=7 ||title=21 |director=15 |writer=25 |airdate=15 |prodcode=10 |episodes=\n\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 34\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n | Title = Racing in the Streets\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|14}}\n | ProdCode = 3ADK-01\n | DirectedBy = [[Brian Hargrove]]\n | WrittenBy = [[Chris Sheridan (writer)|Chris Sheridan]]\n | ShortSummary = To help pay for Erin's grad school tuition, Titus gets involved in illegal street-racing&nbsp;&ndash; despite that he has post-traumatic stress disorder from the car crash that nearly killed him.\n | LineColor = 03C03C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 35\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n | Title = Amy's Birthday\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|21}}\n | ProdCode = 3ADK-03\n | DirectedBy = [[Gary Shimokawa]]\n | WrittenBy = John R. Morey\n | ShortSummary = Erin plans a sixteenth birthday party for her niece Amy, but everything goes downhill when Amy's mother passes out on the cake in a drugged-out stupor, Tommy calls Social Services after seeing Amy's squalid apartment, and Amy's abusive alcoholic stepfather comes home.\n | LineColor = 03C03C\n}}\n{{Episode list\n | EpisodeNumber = 36\n | EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n | Title = Tommy's Not Gay\n | OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2001|11|28}}\n | ProdCode = 3ADK-04\n | DirectedBy = Gary Shimokawa\n | WrittenBy = Christopher Case\n | ShortSummary = Tommy severs ties with his father, Perry, after Perry comes out of the closet and Tommy comes to the realization that he has been copying his father'