{"title_page": "Thiamine deficiency", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Beri beri|the African ethnic group|Kanuri people}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Thiamine deficiency<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| synonyms        = Beriberi, vitamin B<sub>1</sub> deficiency, thiamine-deficiency syndrome<ref name=GARD2015/><ref name=Ad2017/>\n| image           = Beriberi USNLM.jpg\n| caption         = A person with beriberi during the early twentieth century in [[South-East Asia]]\n| field           = [[Neurology]], [[cardiology]], [[pediatrics]]\n| symptoms        = {{Unbulleted list|''Wet:'' Fast heart rate, shortness of breath, leg swelling<ref name=GARD2015/>|''Dry:'' Numbness, confusion, trouble moving the legs, pain<ref name=GARD2015/>}}\n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = Wet, dry, gastrointestinal<ref name=Fer2018/>\n| causes          = Not enough [[thiamine]]<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| risks           = Diet of mostly [[white rice]]; [[alcoholism]], [[dialysis]], chronic [[diarrhea]], [[diuretics]]<ref name=GARD2015/><ref name=CDC2012/>\n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = [[Food fortification]]<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| treatment       = [[Thiamine supplementation]]<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = Rare (US)<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| deaths          = \n}}\n<!-- Definition and symptoms -->\n'''Thiamine deficiency''' is a medical condition of low levels of [[thiamine]] (vitamin B<sub>1</sub>).<ref name=GARD2015/> A severe and chronic form is known as '''beriberi'''.<ref name=GARD2015>{{cite web|title=Beriberi|url=https://rarediseases.info.nih.gov/diseases/9948/beriberi|website=Genetic and Rare Diseases Information Center (GARD) \u2013 an NCATS Program|accessdate=11 November 2017|language=en|date=2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111205215/https://rarediseases.info.nih.gov/diseases/9948/beriberi|archivedate=11 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Hermann\">{{cite book|last1=Hermann|first1=Wolfgang|last2=Obeid|first2=Rima|title=Vitamins in the prevention of human diseases|date=2011|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|location=Berlin|isbn=9783110214482|page=58}}</ref> There are two main types in adults: wet beriberi, and dry beriberi.<ref name=GARD2015/> Wet beriberi affects the [[cardiovascular system]] resulting in a fast heart rate, [[shortness of breath]], and [[pedal edema|leg swelling]].<ref name=GARD2015/> Dry beriberi affects the [[nervous system]] resulting in [[peripheral neuropathy|numbness of the hands and feet]], confusion, trouble moving the legs, and pain.<ref name=GARD2015/> A form with loss of appetite and [[constipation]] may also occur.<ref name=Fer2018>{{cite book|last1=Ferri|first1=Fred F.|title=Ferri's Clinical Advisor 2018 E-Book: 5 Books in 1|date=2017|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9780323529570|page=1368|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=wGclDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1368|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111204713/https://books.google.ca/books?id=wGclDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1368|archivedate=2017-11-11}}</ref> Another type, acute beriberi, is found mostly in babies and presents with loss of appetite, vomiting, [[lactic acidosis]], changes in heart rate, and enlargement of the heart.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gropper, Sareen S. and Smith, Jack L.|edition=6|title=Advanced Nutrition and Human Metabolism|year=2013|publisher=Wadsworth, Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1133104056|page=324}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Cause and diagnosis -->\nRisk factors include a diet of mostly [[white rice]], as well as [[alcoholism]], [[dialysis]], chronic [[diarrhea]], and taking high doses of [[diuretics]].<ref name=GARD2015/><ref name=CDC2012/> Rarely it may be due to a [[genetics|genetic]] condition that results in difficulties absorbing thiamine found in food.<ref name=GARD2015/> [[Wernicke encephalopathy]] and [[Korsakoff syndrome]] are forms of dry beriberi.<ref name=CDC2012>{{cite web|title=Nutrition and Growth Guidelines {{!}} Domestic Guidelines - Immigrant and Refugee Health|url=https://www.cdc.gov/immigrantrefugeehealth/guidelines/domestic/nutrition-growth.html|website=CDC|accessdate=11 November 2017|language=en-us|date=March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111205445/https://www.cdc.gov/immigrantrefugeehealth/guidelines/domestic/nutrition-growth.html|archivedate=11 November 2017}}</ref> Diagnosis is based on symptoms, low levels of thiamine in the urine, high blood [[lactic acid|lactate]], and improvement with treatment.<ref name=Sw2017>{{cite book|last1=Swaiman|first1=Kenneth F.|last2=Ashwal|first2=Stephen|last3=Ferriero|first3=Donna M.|last4=Schor|first4=Nina F.|last5=Finkel|first5=Richard S.|last6=Gropman|first6=Andrea L.|last7=Pearl|first7=Phillip L.|last8=Shevell|first8=Michael|title=Swaiman's Pediatric Neurology E-Book: Principles and Practice|date=2017|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9780323374811|page=e929|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=PJ9tDgAAQBAJ&pg=SL5-PA929|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111204954/https://books.google.ca/books?id=PJ9tDgAAQBAJ&pg=SL5-PA929|archivedate=2017-11-11}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Prevention and treatment -->\nTreatment is by [[thiamine supplementation]], either by mouth or by injection.<ref name=GARD2015/> With treatment, symptoms generally resolve in a couple of weeks.<ref name=Sw2017/> The disease may be prevented at the population level through the [[fortification of food]].<ref name=GARD2015/>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nThiamine deficiency is rare in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thiamin Fact Sheet for Consumers|url=https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Thiamin-Consumer/|publisher=Office of Dietary Supplements (ODS): USA.gov|accessdate=April 10, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065129/https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Thiamin-Consumer/|archivedate=October 29, 2017}}</ref> It remains relatively common in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref name=Ad2017>{{cite journal|last1=Adamolekun|first1=B|last2=Hiffler|first2=L|title=A diagnosis and treatment gap for thiamine deficiency disorders in sub-Saharan Africa?|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|volume=1408|issue=1|pages=15\u201319|date=24 October 2017|doi=10.1111/nyas.13509|pmid=29064578|bibcode=2017NYASA1408...15A|doi-access=free}}</ref> Outbreaks have been seen in [[refugee camps]].<ref name=CDC2012/> Thiamine deficiency has been described for thousands of years in Asia and became more common in the late 1800s with the increased processing of rice.<ref name=Lan2010>{{cite book|last1=Lanska|first1=DJ|title=Chapter 30: historical aspects of the major neurological vitamin deficiency disorders: the water-soluble B vitamins.|journal=Handbook of Clinical Neurology|date=2010|volume=95|pages=445\u201376|doi=10.1016/S0072-9752(08)02130-1|pmid=19892133|isbn=9780444520098}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\n===Beriberi===\nSymptoms of beriberi include weight loss, [[emotion]]al disturbances, impaired [[sensory perception]], [[muscle weakness|weakness]] and [[pain]] in the limbs, and periods of irregular [[heart rate]]. [[Edema]] (swelling of bodily tissues) is common. It may increase the amount of [[lactic acid]] and [[pyruvic acid]] within the blood. In advanced cases, the disease may cause [[high-output cardiac failure]] and death.\n\nSymptoms may occur concurrently with those of [[Wernicke's encephalopathy]], a primarily neurological thiamine-deficiency related condition.\n\nBeriberi is divided into four categories as follows. The first three are historical and the fourth, gastrointestinal beriberi, was recognized in 2004:\n*''Dry beriberi'' especially affects the peripheral nervous system.\n*''Wet beriberi'' especially affects the cardiovascular system and other bodily systems.\n*''Infantile beriberi'' affects the babies of malnourished mothers.\n*''Gastrointestinal beriberi'' affects the digestive system and other bodily systems.\n\n====Dry beriberi====\nDry beriberi causes wasting and partial [[paralysis]] resulting from damaged peripheral [[nerve]]s.  It is also referred to as endemic neuritis. It is characterized by:\n*Difficulty in walking\n*Tingling or loss of sensation ([[Paresthesia|numbness]]) in hands and feet \n*Loss of tendon reflexes<ref name=Katsura/>\n*Loss of muscle function or paralysis of the lower legs\n*Mental confusion/speech difficulties\n*Pain\n*Involuntary eye movements ([[Pathologic nystagmus|nystagmus]])\n*Vomiting\n\nA selective impairment of the large proprioceptive sensory fibers without motor impairment can occur and present as a prominent sensory [[ataxia]], which is a loss of balance and coordination due to loss of the proprioceptive inputs from the periphery and loss of position sense.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/nrneurol.2010.16 |title=Subacute sensory ataxia and optic neuropathy with thiamine deficiency|year=2010 |last1=Spinazzi |first1=Marco |last2=Angelini |first2=Corrado |last3=Patrini |first3=Cesare|journal=Nature Reviews Neurology |volume=6 |issue=5 |pages=288\u201393 |pmid=20308997}}</ref>\n\n===Brain disease===\n[[Wernicke's encephalopathy]] (WE), [[Korsakoff's syndrome]] (alcohol amnestic disorder), [[Wernicke\u2013Korsakoff syndrome]] are forms of dry beriberi.<ref name=CDC2012/>\n\nWernicke's encephalopathy is the most frequently encountered manifestation of thiamine deficiency in Western society,<ref name=\"Kril\">{{cite journal | author = Kril JJ | title = Neuropathology of thiamine deficiency disorders | journal = Metab Brain Dis | year = 1996 | volume = 11| issue=1 | pages=9\u201317 | doi = 10.1007/BF02080928 | pmid = 8815394}}</ref><ref>For an interesting discussion on thiamine fortification of foods, specifically targetting beer, see {{cite journal\n |journal     = Medical Journal of Australia\n |title       = Wernicke's encephalopathy and thiamine fortification of food: time for a new direction?\n |url         = http://www.mja.com.au/public/issues/jun1/drew/drew.html\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110831104941/http://www.mja.com.au/public/issues/jun1/drew/drew.html\n |archivedate = 2011-08-31\n}}</ref> though it may also occur in patients with impaired nutrition from other causes, such as gastrointestinal disease,<ref name=\"Kril\"/> those with [[HIV/AIDS]], and with the injudicious administration of [[route of administration#Local or systemic effect|parenteral]] glucose or [[hyperalimentation]] without adequate B-vitamin supplementation.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Butterworth RF, Gaudreau C, Vincelette J, etal | journal= Metab Brain Dis |year=1991 |volume=6 |pages=207\u201312 |doi=10.1007/BF00996920 |title=Thiamine deficiency and wernicke's encephalopathy in AIDS |pmid=1812394 |issue=4}}</ref> This is a striking neuro-psychiatric disorder characterized by paralysis of eye movements, abnormal stance and gait, and markedly deranged mental function.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Harper C. |title=Wernicke's encephalopathy, a more common disease than realised (a neuropathological study of 51 cases)|journal =J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry |year=1979|volume=42|pages=226\u2013231|doi=10.1136/jnnp.42.3.226|pmid=438830|issue=3|pmc=490724}}</ref>\n\n[[Korsakoff's syndrome]] is, in general, considered to occur with deterioration of brain function in patients initially diagnosed with WE.<ref>McCollum EV  ''A History of Nutrition''. Cambridge, MA: Riverside Press, Houghton Mifflin; 1957.</ref> This is an amnestic-confabulatory syndrome characterized by [[retrograde amnesia|retrograde]] and [[anterograde amnesia]], impairment of conceptual functions, and decreased spontaneity and initiative.<ref name=\"Butterworth RF. Thiamin 2006\">Butterworth RF. Thiamin. In: Shils ME, Shike M, Ross AC, Caballero B, Cousins RJ, editors. Modern Nutrition in Health and Disease, 10th ed. Baltimore: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; 2006.</ref>\n\nAlcoholics may have thiamine deficiency because of the following:\n* Inadequate nutritional intake:  Alcoholics tend to intake less than the recommended amount of thiamine.\n* Decreased uptake of thiamine from the GI tract:  Active transport of thiamine into enterocytes is disturbed during acute alcohol exposure.\n* Liver thiamine stores are reduced due to hepatic steatosis or fibrosis.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Butterworth RF | journal=Drug Alcohol Rev |year=1993|volume=12|pages=315\u201322|doi=10.1080/09595239300185371|title=Pathophysiologic mechanisms responsible for the reversible (thiamine-responsive) and irreversible (thiamine non-responsive) neurological symptoms of Wernicke's encephalopathy|pmid=16840290|issue=3}}</ref>\n* Impaired thiamine utilization:  Magnesium, which is required for the binding of thiamine to thiamine-using enzymes within the cell, is also deficient due to chronic alcohol consumption.  The inefficient utilization of any thiamine that does reach the cells will further exacerbate the thiamine deficiency.\n* Ethanol ''per se'' inhibits thiamine transport in the gastrointestinal system and blocks phosphorylation of thiamine to its cofactor form (ThDP).<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Rindi G, Imarisio L, Patrini C |journal = Biochem Pharmacol | year = 1986 |volume=35 |pages=3903\u20138|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(86)90002-X|title=Effects of acute and chronic ethanol administration on regional thiamin pyrophosphokinase activity of the rat brain|pmid=3022743|issue=22}}</ref>\n\nFollowing improved nutrition and the removal of alcohol consumption, some impairments linked with thiamine deficiency are reversed, in particular poor brain functionality, although in more severe cases, Wernicke\u2013Korsakoff syndrome leaves permanent damage.  (See [[delirium tremens]].)\n\n===Wet beriberi===\nWet beriberi affects the [[heart]] and circulatory system. It is sometimes fatal, as it causes a combination of [[congestive heart failure|heart failure]] and weakening of the [[capillary]] walls, which causes the peripheral tissues to become edematous. Wet beriberi is characterized by:\n*Increased heart rate\n*[[Vasodilation]] leading to decreased systemic vascular resistance, and high output heart failure<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 11242561|doi=10.1007/s11936-001-0070-1| year = 2001| last1 = Anand| first1 = I. S.| title = High Output Cardiac Failure| journal = Current Treatment Options in Cardiovascular Medicine| volume = 3| issue = 2| pages = 151\u2013159| last2 = Florea| first2 = V. G.}}</ref>\n*Elevated [[jugular venous pressure]]<ref name=twomodes>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.3.5774.567 |title=Cardiac Beriberi: Two Modes of Presentation |year=1971 |last1=McIntyre |first1=Neil |last2=Stanley |first2=Nigel N. |journal=BMJ |volume=3 |issue=5774 |pages=567\u20139 |pmid=5571454 |pmc=1798841}}</ref>\n*Dyspnea (shortness of breath) on exertion\n*Paroxysmal nocturnal [[dyspnea]]\n*Peripheral [[oedema|edema]]<ref name=twomodes/> (swelling of lower legs)\n*[[Dilated cardiomyopathy]]\n\n===Gastrointestinal beriberi===\nGastrointestinal beriberi causes abdominal pain. Gastrointestinal beriberi is characterized by:\n*Abdominal pain\n*Nausea\n*Vomiting\n*Lactic acidosis<ref>{{cite journal | author = Donnino M | year = 2004 | title = Gastrointestinal Beriberi: A Previously Unrecognized Syndrome | url = | journal = Ann Intern Med | volume = 141 | issue = 11| pages = 898\u2013899 | doi = 10.7326/0003-4819-141-11-200412070-00035 | pmid = 15583247 }}</ref><ref>Duca, J., Lum, C., & Lo, A. (2015). Elevated Lactate Secondary to Gastrointestinal Beriberi. J GEN INTERN MED Journal of General Internal Medicine</ref>\n\n===Infants===\nInfantile beriberi usually occurs between two and six months of age in children whose mothers have inadequate thiamine intake. It may present as either wet or dry beriberi.<ref name=Ad2017/>\n\nIn the acute form, the baby develops [[dyspnea]] and [[cyanosis]] and soon dies of [[heart failure]]. These symptoms may be described in infantile beriberi:\n*Hoarseness, where the child makes moves to moan but emits no sound or just faint moans<ref name=latham>{{cite book | chapter-url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/006/w0073s/w0073s0k.htm | title = Human nutrition in the developing world (Food and Nutrition Series \u2013 No. 29) | chapter = Chapter 16. Beriberi and thiamine deficiency | first = Michael C. | last = Latham | publisher = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) | issn = 1014-3181 | location = Rome | year = 1997 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140203001516/http://www.fao.org/docrep/006/w0073s/w0073s0k.htm | archivedate = 2014-02-03 }}</ref> caused by nerve paralysis<ref name=Katsura/>\n*Weight loss, becoming thinner and then [[marasmic]] as the disease progresses<ref name=latham/>\n*Vomiting<ref name=latham/>\n*Diarrhea<ref name=latham/>\n*Pale skin<ref name=Katsura>{{cite journal | url = http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_62_(chp9).pdf | first = E. | last = Katsura | first2 = T. | last2 = Oiso | title = Chapter 9. Beriberi | journal = World Health Organization Monograph Series No. 62: Nutrition in Preventive Medicine | editor-first = G.H. | editor-last = Beaton | editor2-first = J.M. | editor2-last = Bengoa | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva | year = 1976 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708000808/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_62_(chp9).pdf | archivedate = 2011-07-08 }}</ref>\n*Edema<ref name=Katsura/><ref name=latham/>\n*Ill temper<ref name=Katsura/>\n*Alterations of the cardiovascular system, especially [[tachycardia]] (rapid heart rate)<ref name=Katsura/>\n*[[Convulsions]] occasionally observed in the terminal stages<ref name=latham/>\n\n==Cause==\nBeriberi may also be caused by shortcomings other than inadequate intake: [[digestive disease|diseases]] or operations on the digestive tract, [[alcoholism]],<ref name=twomodes/> [[dialysis]], [[genetic deficiencies]], etc. All these causes mainly affect the central nervous system, and provoke the development of what is known as [[Wernicke's encephalopathy|Wernicke's disease or Wernicke's encephalopathy]].\n\nWernicke's disease is one of the most prevalent neurological or neuropsychiatric diseases.<ref name=\"Cernicchiaro 2007\">{{citation| url = http://enfermedad-de-wernicke.weebly.com/| title = Enfermedad de Wernicke (o Encefalopat\u00eda de Wernicke). Monitoring an acute and recovered case for twelve years.| trans-title = Wernicke\u00b4s Disease (or Wernicke\u00b4s Encephalopathy)| first = Luis| last = Cernicchiaro| language = Spanish| year = 2007| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130522155106/http://enfermedad-de-wernicke.weebly.com/| archivedate = 2013-05-22}}</ref> In [[autopsy]] series, features of Wernicke lesions are observed in approximately 2% of general cases.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/794583-overview#a0156 | title = Wernicke Encephalopathy | first = Philip N | last = Salen | editor-first = Rick | editor-last = Kulkarni | website = Medscape | date = 1 March 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130512085230/http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/794583-overview#a0156 | archivedate = 12 May 2013 }}</ref> Medical record research shows that about 85% had not been diagnosed, although only 19% would be asymptomatic. In children, only 58% were diagnosed. In [[alcohol abuse]]rs, autopsy series showed neurological damages at rates of 12.5% or more. Mortality caused by Wernicke's disease reaches 17% of diseases, which means 3.4/1000 or about 25 million contemporaries.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Harper |first = CG | last2 = Giles |first2 = M |last3 = Finlay-Jones | first3= R | pmid = 3701343  | journal = J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry | date = April 1986 | volume = 49 | issue = 4 | pages = 341\u20135 | title = Clinical signs in the Wernicke-Korsakoff complex: a retrospective analysis of 131 cases diagnosed at necropsy | doi=10.1136/jnnp.49.4.341 | pmc=1028756}}</ref><ref name=Harper1979>{{cite journal | last = Harper |first = C | pmid = 438830 | journal = J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry | date = March 1979 | volume = 42 | issue = 3 | pages = 226\u201331 | title = Wernicke's encephalopathy: a more common disease than realised. A neuropathological study of 51 cases | doi=10.1136/jnnp.42.3.226 | pmc=490724}}</ref> The number of people with Wernicke's disease may be even higher, considering that early stages may have dysfunctions prior to the production of observable lesions at necropsy. In addition, uncounted numbers of people can experience fetal damage and subsequent diseases.\n\n===Genetics===\nGenetic diseases of thiamine transport are rare but serious. [[Thiamine responsive megaloblastic anemia]] (TRMA) with [[diabetes mellitus]] and [[sensorineural deafness]]<ref>{{cite journal | title =Thiamine Responsive Megaloblastic Anemia with severe diabetes mellitus and sensorineural deafness (TRMA) |pmid=249270 | year =1978 | last1 =Slater | first1 =PV | volume =7 | issue =11 | pages =40\u20133 | journal =The Australian Nurses' Journal}}</ref> is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutations in the gene [[SLC19A2]],<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 603941 |date=Dec 1977 |author1=Kopriva, V |author2=Bilkovic, R |author3=Licko, T | title = Tumours of the small intestine (author's transl) | volume = 31 | issue = 8 | pages = 549\u201353 | issn = 0009-0565 | journal = Ceskoslovenska Gastroenterologie a Vyziva}}</ref> a high affinity thiamine transporter. TRMA patients do not show signs of systemic thiamine deficiency, suggesting redundancy in the thiamine transport system. This has led to the discovery of a second high-affinity thiamine transporter, [[SLC19A3]].<ref>{{cite journal | pmid =606152 |date=Dec 1977 | author =Beissel, J | title =The role of right catheterization in valvular prosthesis surveillance (author's transl) | volume =26 | issue =6 | pages =587\u20139 | issn =0003-3928 | journal =Annales de Cardiologie et d'Ang\u00e9iologie}}</ref><ref>{{OMIM|249270}}</ref> [[Leigh disease]] (subacute necrotising encephalomyelopathy) is an inherited disorder that affects mostly infants in the first years of life and is invariably fatal. Pathological similarities between Leigh disease and WE led to the hypothesis that the cause was a defect in thiamine metabolism. One of the most consistent findings has been an abnormality of the activation of the [[pyruvate dehydrogenase]] complex.<ref>Butterworth RF. Pyruvate dehydrogenase deficiency disorders. In: McCandless DW, ed. ''Cerebral Energy Metabolism and Metabolic Encephalopathy''. Plenum Publishing Corp.; 1985.</ref>\n\nMutations in the [[SLC19A3]] gene have been linked to [[biotin-thiamine responsive basal ganglia disease]]<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK169615/ Biotin-Thiamine-Responsive Basal Ganglia Disease - GeneReviews\u00ae - NCBI Bookshelf<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509171903/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK169615/ |date=2018-05-09 }}</ref>, which is treated with pharmacological doses of thiamine and [[biotin]], another [[B vitamin]].\n\nOther disorders in which a putative role for thiamine has been implicated include [[subacute necrotising encephalomyelopathy]], [[opsoclonic cerebellopathy]] (a paraneoplastic syndrome), and [[Nigerian seasonal ataxia]]. In addition, several inherited disorders of ThDP-dependent enzymes have been reported,<ref>Blass JP. Inborn errors of pyruvate metabolism. In: Stanbury JB, Wyngaarden JB, Frederckson DS et al., eds. ''Metabolic Basis of Inherited Disease''. 5th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill, 1983.</ref> which may respond to thiamine treatment.<ref name=\"Butterworth RF. Thiamin 2006\"/>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\nThiamine in the human body has a half-life of 18 days and is quickly exhausted, particularly when metabolic demands exceed intake. A derivative of thiamine, [[thiamine pyrophosphate]] (TPP), is a cofactor involved in the [[citric acid cycle]], as well as connecting the [[Glycolysis|breakdown of sugars]] with the citric acid cycle. The citric acid cycle is a central metabolic pathway involved in the regulation of carbohydrate, lipid, and amino acid metabolism, and its disruption due to thiamine deficiency inhibits the production of many molecules including the neurotransmitters [[glutamic acid]] and [[GABA]].<ref name=Sechi>{{cite journal|last=Sechi|first=G|last2=Serra |first2=A |title=Wernicke's encephalopathy: new clinical settings and recent advances in diagnosis and management|journal=Lancet Neurology|date=May 2007 | volume=6 | issue=5 | pages=442\u201355 | pmid=17434099 |doi=10.1016/S1474-4422(07)70104-7 }}</ref> Additionally thiamine may also be directly involved in [[Neuromodulation (biology)|neuromodulation]].<ref name=Hirsch>{{cite journal|last=Hirsch |first=JA| last2=Parrott |first2=J |title=New considerations on the neuromodulatory role of thiamine |journal=Pharmacology |date=2012| volume=89 | issue=1\u20132 | pages=111\u20136 | pmid=22398704 |doi=10.1159/000336339 }}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\n[[File:Thiochromes.jpg|thumb|Oxidation of thiamine derivatives to fluorescent thiochromes by potassium ferricyanide under alkaline conditions]]\n\nA positive diagnosis test for thiamine deficiency involves measuring the activity of the enzyme [[transketolase]] in [[erythrocyte]]s (Erythrocyte transketolase activation assay). Alternatively, thiamine and its phosphphosphorylated derivatives, can directly be detected in whole blood, tissues, foods, animal feed, and pharmaceutical preparations following the conversion of thiamine to [[fluorescent]] thiochrome derivatives (Thiochrome assay) and separation by [[high-performance liquid chromatography]] (HPLC).<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0003-2697(91)90505-N | last1 = Bettendorff | first1 = L | last2 = Peeters | first2 = M. | last3 = Jouan | first3 = C. | last4 = Wins | first4 = P. | last5 = Schoffeniels | first5 = E. |name-list-format=vanc | year = 1991 | title = Determination of thiamin and its phosphate esters in cultured neurons and astrocytes using an ion-pair reversed-phase high-performance liquid chromatographic method | url = | journal = Anal. Biochem. | volume = 198 | issue = 1| pages = 52\u201359 | pmid = 1789432 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.jpba.2004.08.038 | last1 = Losa | first1 = R | last2 = Sierra | first2 = MI | last3 = Fern\u00e1ndez | first3 = A | last4 = Blanco | first4 = D | last5 = Buesa | first5 = JM. |name-list-format=vanc | year = 2005 | title = Determination of thiamine and its phosphorylated forms in human plasma, erythrocytes and urine by HPLC and fluorescence detection: a preliminary study on cancer patients | url = | journal = J Pharm Biomed Anal | volume = 37 | issue = 5| pages = 1025\u20131029 | pmid = 15862682 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1373/clinchem.2007.099077 | last1 = Lu | first1 = J | last2 = Frank | first2 = EL. |name-list-format=vanc |date=May 2008 | title = Rapid HPLC measurement of thiamine and its phosphate esters in whole blood | url = | journal = Clin. Chem. | volume = 54 | issue = 5| pages = 901\u2013906 | pmid = 18356241 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Capillary electrophoresis (CE) techniques and in-capillary enzyme reaction methods have emerged as alternative techniques in quantifying and monitoring thiamine levels in samples.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Shabangi | first1 = M | last2 = Sutton | first2 = JA. |name-list-format=vanc | year = 2005 | title = Separation of thiamin and its phosphate esters by capillary zone electrophoresis and its application to the analysis of water-soluble vitamins | url = | journal = Journal of Pharmaceutical and Biomedical Analysis | volume = 38 | issue = 1| pages = 66\u201371 | pmid = 15907621 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpba.2004.11.061 }}</ref>\nThe normal thiamine concentration in EDTA-blood is about 20-100&nbsp;\u00b5g/l.\n\n==Treatment==\nMany people with beriberi can be treated with thiamine alone.<ref>Nguyen-Khoa, Dieu-Thu  [http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/116930-treatment Beriberi (Thiamine Deficiency) Treatment & Management] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324014710/http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/116930-treatment |date=2014-03-24 }}. Mescape</ref> Given thiamine intravenously (and later orally), rapid and dramatic <ref name=twomodes/> recovery can occur within hours. If concentrated thiamine supplements are not available, thiamine-rich diets (e.g. [[whole wheat bread|whole grain brown bread]]) will lead to recovery, though at a much slower rate.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nFollowing thiamine treatment, rapid improvement occurs, in general, within 24 hours.<ref name=\"Tanphaichitr\">Tanphaichitr V. Thiamin. In: Shils ME, Olsen JA, Shike M et al., editors. ''Modern Nutrition in Health and Disease''. 9th ed. Baltimore: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; 1999</ref> Improvements of peripheral neuropathy may require several months of thiamine treatment.<ref>Maurice V, Adams RD, Collins GH. ''The Wernicke-Korsakoff Syndrome and Related Neurologic Disorders Due to Alcoholism and Malnutrition''. 2nd ed. Philadelphia: FA Davis, 1989.</ref>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nHistorically, beriberi was associated with a diet based on polished rice ([[white rice]]). When the relationship between the polishing of rice and the disease became clear, the deficiency could be treated and prevented by including inexpensive rice [[bran]] in the diet, among other things. Beriberi caused by inadequate nutritional intake of thiamine is rare today in developed countries{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} because of quality of food and the fact that many foods are fortified with vitamins.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} There are generally no reliable statistics for beriberi in developed or developing countries prior to the 20th century.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nBeriberi is a recurrent nutritional disease in detention houses, even in this century. In 1999, an outbreak of beriberi occurred in a detention center in Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite journal|year=2003|title=Outbreak of beriberi among illegal mainland Chinese immigrants at a detention center in Taiwan|journal=Public Health Rep|volume=118|issue=1|pages=59\u201364|doi=10.1093/phr/118.1.59|pmid=12604765|vauthors=Chen KT, Twu SJ, Chiou ST, Pan WH, Chang HJ, Serdula MK|pmc=1497506}}</ref> High rates of illness and death in overcrowded Haitian jails in 2007 were traced to the traditional practice of washing rice before cooking.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2007/01/haiti-mysterious-prison-ailment-traced-to-us-rice/ |title=Haiti: Mysterious Prison Ailment Traced to U.S. Rice |first1=Jeb |last1=Sprague |first2=Eunida |last2=Alexandra |agency=Inter Press Service |date=17 January 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530034501/http://www.ipsnews.net/2007/01/haiti-mysterious-prison-ailment-traced-to-us-rice/ |archivedate=30 May 2013 }}</ref> In the [[Ivory Coast]], among a group of prisoners with heavy punishment, 64% were affected by beriberi. Before beginning treatment, prisoners exhibited symptoms of dry or wet beriberi with neurological signs (tingling: 41%), cardiovascular signs (dyspnoea: 42%, thoracic pain: 35%), and [[edema]]s of the lower limbs (51%). With treatment the rate of healing was about 97%.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/s13149-011-0136-6| pmid = 21336653| title = Le b\u00e9rib\u00e9ri, maladie nutritionnelle r\u00e9currente en milieu carc\u00e9ral en C\u00f4te-d'Ivoire| journal = Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Pathologie Exotique| volume = 104| issue = 5| pages = 347\u2013351| year = 2011| last1 = Ak\u00e9-Tano | first1 = O.| last2 = Konan | first2 = E. Y.| last3 = Tetchi | first3 = E. O.| last4 = Ekou | first4 = F. K.| last5 = Ekra | first5 = D.| last6 = Coulibaly | first6 = A.| last7 = Dagnan | first7 = N. S.}}</ref>\n\nPopulations under extreme stress may be at higher risk for beriberi. [[Forced displacement|Displaced populations]], such as [[refugee]]s from war, are susceptible to micronutritional deficiency, including beriberi.<ref name=prinzo2009>{{cite journal |doi=10.1079/PNS2002151 |title=Meeting the challenges of micronutrient deficiencies in emergency-affected populations |year=2009 |last1=Prinzo |first1=Z. Weise |last2=de Benoist |first2=B. |journal=Proceedings of the Nutrition Society |volume=61 |issue=2 |pmid=12133207 |url=http://www.who.int/nutrition/publications/micronutrients/PNSvol61no2may02.pdf |pages=251\u20137 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019151311/http://www.who.int/nutrition/publications/micronutrients/PNSvol61no2may02.pdf |archivedate=2012-10-19 }}</ref> The severe nutritional deprivation caused by [[famine]] also can cause beriberis, although symptoms may be overlooked in clinical assessment or masked by other famine-related problems.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://fex.ennonline.net/1/diagnosing.aspx |title=Diagnosing Beriberi in Emergency Situations |first1=Mike |last1=Golden |journal=Field Exchange |date=May 1997 |issue=1 |page=18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019200706/http://fex.ennonline.net/1/diagnosing.aspx |archivedate=2012-10-19 }}</ref> An extreme weight-loss [[Dieting|diet]] can, rarely, induce a famine-like state and the accompanying beriberi.<ref name=twomodes/>\n\n==History==\nEarliest written descriptions of thiamine deficiency are from Ancient China in the context of [[chinese medicine]]. One of the earliest is by [[Ge Hong]] in his book ''Zhou hou bei ji fang'' (Emergency Formulas to Keep up Your Sleeve) written sometime during the [[3rd century]]. Hong called the illness by the name ''jiao qi'', which can be interpreted as \"foot [[qi]]\". He described the symptoms to include swelling, weakness and numbness of the feet. He also acknowledged that the illness could be deadly, and claimed that it could be cured by eating certain foods such as fermented soybeans in wine. Better known examples of early descriptions of \"foot qi\" are by [[Chao Yuanfang]] (who lived during 550\u2013630) in his book ''Zhu bing yuan hou lun'' (Sources and Symptoms of All Diseases)<ref name=\":0\">HA Smith, p. 26-28</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Benedict|first=CA|date=2018-10-25|title=Forgotten Disease: Illnesses Transformed in Chinese Medicine by Hilary A. Smith (review)|journal=Bulletin of the History of Medicine|volume=92|issue=3|pages=550\u2013551|doi=10.1353/bhm.2018.0059|issn=1086-3176}}</ref> and by [[Sun Simiao]] (581\u2013682) in his book ''Bei ji qian jin yao fang'' (Essential Emergency Formulas Worth a Thousand in Gold).<ref>HA Smith, p. 44</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shen-nong.com/eng/history/suitang.html|title=TCM history V the Sui & Tang Dynasties|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714124755/http://www.shen-nong.com/eng/history/suitang.html|archivedate=2017-07-14|url-status=live|accessdate=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itmonline.org/arts/sunsimiao.htm|title=Sun Simiao: Author of the Earliest Chinese Encyclopedia for Clinical Practice|accessdate=2007-06-15 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704150247/http://www.itmonline.org/arts/sunsimiao.htm |archivedate=2007-07-04}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century, beriberi was studied by [[Takaki Kanehiro]], a British-trained Japanese medical doctor of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]].<ref name=Takaki>{{cite journal |first1=Yoshinori |last1=Itokawa |year=1976 |title=Kanehiro Takaki (1849\u20131920): A Biographical Sketch |journal=Journal of Nutrition |pmid=772183 |volume=106 |issue=5 |pages=581\u20138|doi=10.1093/jn/106.5.581 }}</ref> Beriberi was a serious problem in the Japanese navy: Sailors fell ill an average of four times a year in the period 1878 to 1881, and 35% were cases of beriberi.<ref name=Takaki/> In 1883, Takaki learned of a very high incidence of beriberi among cadets on a training mission from Japan to Hawaii, via New Zealand and South America. The voyage lasted more than nine months and resulted in 169 cases of sickness and 25 deaths on a ship of 376 men. With the support of the Japanese Navy, he conducted an experiment in which another ship was deployed on the same route, except that its crew was fed a diet of meat, fish, barley, rice, and beans. At the end of the voyage, this crew had only 14 cases of beriberi and no deaths. This convinced Takaki and the Japanese Navy that diet was the cause.<ref name=Takaki/> In 1884, Takaki observed that beriberi was common among low-ranking crew who were often provided free rice and thus ate little else, but not among crews of Western navies, nor among Japanese officers who consumed a more varied diet.\n\nIn 1897, [[Christiaan Eijkman]], a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[physician]] and [[pathologist]], demonstrated that beriberi is caused by poor diet, and discovered that feeding unpolished rice (instead of the polished variety) to chickens helped to prevent beriberi. The following year, Sir [[Frederick Hopkins]] postulated that some foods contained \"accessory factors\"\u2014in addition to proteins, carbohydrates, fats, and salt\u2014that were necessary for the functions of the human body.<ref name=\"Challem\">{{cite web | first = Jack | last = Challem | year = 1997 | url = http://www.thenutritionreporter.com/history_of_vitamins.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100608223713/http://www.thenutritionreporter.com/history_of_vitamins.html | archivedate = 8 June 2010 | title = The Past, Present and Future of Vitamins}}{{MEDRS|date=July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation | url = http://nobelprize.org/educational_games/medicine/vitamin_b1/eijkman.html | title = Christiaan Eijkman, Beriberi and Vitamin B1 | publisher = Nobelprize.org, Nobel Media AB | accessdate = 8 July 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100117191212/http://nobelprize.org/educational_games/medicine/vitamin_b1/eijkman.html | archivedate = 17 January 2010 }}</ref> In 1901, [[Gerrit Grijns]], a Dutch physician and assistant to [[Christiaan Eijkman]] in the Netherlands, correctly interpreted beriberi as a deficiency syndrome,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Grijns |first1=G. |year=1901 |title=Over polyneuritis gallinarum |journal=Geneeskundig Tijdschrift voor Nederlandsch-Indie |volume=43 |pages=3\u2013110}}</ref> and between 1910 and 1913, [[Edward Bright Vedder]] established that an extract of [[rice bran]] is a treatment for beriberi.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} In 1929, Eijkman and Hopkins were awarded the [[Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine]] for their discoveries.\n\n===Etymology===\nAlthough according to the [[Oxford English Dictionary]], the term \"beriberi\" comes from a [[Sinhala language|Sinhalese]] phrase meaning \"weak, weak\" or \"I cannot, I cannot\", the word being [[reduplication|duplicated]] for emphasis,<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]: \"Beri-beri&nbsp;... a Cingalese word, f. ''beri'' weakness, the reduplication being intensive&nbsp;...\", page 203, 1937</ref> the origin of the phrase is questionable. It has also been suggested to come from Hindi, Arabic and a few other languages, with many meanings like \"weakness\", \"sailor\" and even \"sheep\". Such suggested origins were listed by [[Heinrich Botho Scheube]] among others. [[Edward Vedder]] wrote in his book ''Beriberi'' (1913) that \"it is impossible to definitely trace the origin of the word beriberi\". Word ''berbere'' was used in writing at least as early as 1568 by [[Diogo do Couto]], when he described the deficiency in India.<ref>HA Smith, p. 118-119</ref>\n\n\"Kakke\", which is a Japanese synonym for thiamine deficiency, comes from the way \"jiao qi\" is pronounced in Japanese.<ref name=\":2\">HA Smith, p. 149</ref> \"Jiao qi\" is an old word used in Chinese medicine to describe beriberi.<ref name=\":0\" /> \"Kakke\" is supposed to have entered into the Japanese language sometime between the 6th and 8th centuries.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Other animals==\n\n===Poultry===\nAs most feedstuffs used in poultry diets contain enough quantities of vitamins to meet the requirements in this species, deficiencies in this vitamin do not occur with commercial diets. This was, at least, the opinion in the 1960s.<ref>''Merck Veterinary Manual'', ed 1967, pp 1440-1441.</ref>\n\nMature chickens show signs three weeks after being fed a deficient diet. In young chicks, it can appear before two weeks of age.\n\nOnset is sudden in young chicks. There is anorexia and an unsteady gait. Later on, there are locomotor signs, beginning with an apparent paralysis of the flexor of the toes. The characteristic position is called \"stargazing\", meaning a chick \"sitting on its hocks and the head in [[opisthotonos]]\".\n\nResponse to administration of the vitamin is rather quick, occurring a few hours later.<ref>R.E. Austic and M.L. Scott, Nutritional deficiency diseases, in ''Diseases of poultry'', ed. by M.S. Hofstad, Iowa State University Press, Ames, Iowa, USA {{ISBN|0-8138-0430-2}}, p. 50.</ref><ref>The disease is described more carefully here: [http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/206934.htm merckvetmanual.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222050129/http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm%2Fbc%2F206934.htm |date=2008-12-22 }}</ref>\n\nDifferential diagnosis include [[riboflavin deficiency]] and [[avian encephalomyelitis]]. In riboflavin deficiency, the \"curled toes\" is a characteristic symptom. Muscle tremor is typical of avian encephalomyelitis. A therapeutic [[medical diagnosis|diagnosis]] can be tried by supplementing thiamine only in the affected bird. If the animals do not respond in a few hours, thiamine deficiency can be excluded.\n\n===Ruminants===\n[[Polioencephalomalacia]] (PEM) is the most common thiamine deficiency disorder in young ruminant and nonruminant animals.  Symptoms of PEM include a profuse, but transient, diarrhea, listlessness, circling movements, star gazing or opisthotonus (head drawn back over neck), and muscle tremors.<ref>National Research Council. 1996. ''Nutrient Requirements of Beef Cattle'', Seventh Revised Ed. Washington, D.C.: National Academy Press.</ref> The most common cause is high-carbohydrate feeds, leading to the overgrowth of thiaminase-producing bacteria, but dietary ingestion of thiaminase (e.g., in [[bracken]] fern), or inhibition of thiamine absorption by high sulfur intake are also possible.<ref>[http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/102000.htm Polioencephalomalacia: Introduction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233122/http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm%2Fbc%2F102000.htm |date=2016-03-03 }}, ''Merck Veterinary Manual''</ref>  Another cause of PEM is ''Clostridium sporogenes'' or ''Bacillus aneurinolyticus'' infection. These bacteria produce [[thiaminase]]s that will cause an acute thiamine deficiency in the affected animal.<ref>[http://www.aces.edu/pubs/docs/U/UNP-0065/ Polioencephalomacia: Introduction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528043219/http://www.aces.edu/pubs/docs/U/UNP-0065/ |date=2010-05-28 }}, \"ACES Publications\"</ref>\n\n===Snakes===\nSnakes that consume a diet largely composed of goldfish and feeder minnows are susceptible to developing thiamine deficiency. This is often a problem observed in captivity when keeping garter and ribbon snakes that are fed a goldfish-exclusive diet, as these fish contain thiaminase, an enzyme that breaks down thiamine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264981292 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-09-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913231717/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264981292_Update_on_Common_Nutritional_Disorders_of_Captive_Reptiles |archivedate=2017-09-13 }}</ref>\n\n===Wild birds and fish===\nThiamine deficiency has been identified as the cause of a paralytic disease affecting wild birds in the Baltic Sea area dating back to 1982.<ref name=\"Balk\">{{cite journal | last1 = Balk | first1 = L | last2 = H\u00e4gerroth | first2 = PA | last3 = Akerman | first3 = G | last4 = Hanson | first4 = M | last5 = Tj\u00e4rnlund | first5 = U | last6 = Hansson | first6 = T | last7 = Hallgrimsson | first7 = GT | last8 = Zeb\u00fchr | first8 = Y | last9 = Broman | first9 = D | year = 2009 | title = Wild birds of declining European species are dying from a thiamine deficiency syndrome | url = | journal = Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A | volume = 106 | issue = 29| pages = 12001\u201312006 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0902903106 | pmc = 2715476 | pmid = 19597145 | last10 = M\u00f6rner | first10 = T. | last11 = Sundberg | first11 = H. |display-authors=etal| bibcode = 2009PNAS..10612001B }}</ref> In this condition, there is difficulty in keeping the wings folded along the side of the body when resting, loss of the ability to fly and voice, with eventual paralysis of the wings and legs and death. It affects primarily 0.5\u20131&nbsp;kg sized birds such as the [[European herring gull|herring gull]] (''Larus argentatus''), [[common starling]] (''Sturnus vulgaris'') and [[common eider]] (''Somateria mollissima''). Researches noted, \"Because the investigated species occupy a wide range of ecological niches and positions in the food web, we are open to the possibility that other animal classes may suffer from thiamine deficiency as well.\"<ref name=\"Balk\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;12006</sup>\n\nIn the counties of [[Blekinge]] and [[Sk\u00e5ne]] (southernmost [[Sweden]]), mass deaths of several bird species, especially the [[European herring gull]], have been observed since the early 2000s. More recently, species of other classes seems to be affected. High mortality of [[Atlantic Salmon|salmon]] (''Salmo salar'') in the river [[M\u00f6rrums\u00e5n]] is reported, and mammals such as the [[Moose|Eurasian Elk]] (''Alces alces'') have died in unusually high numbers. Lack of thiamine is the common denominator where analysis is done. In April 2012, the County Administrative Board of Blekinge found the situation so alarming that they asked the Swedish government to set up a closer investigation.<ref name=\"L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Blekinge l\u00e4n\">{{cite journal | last1 = Blekinge l\u00e4n | first1 = L\u00e4nsstyrelsen | year = 2013 | title = 2012-04-15 500-1380-13 F\u00f6rh\u00f6jd d\u00f6dlighet hos f\u00e5gel, lax og \u00e4lg | url = http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/blekinge/SiteCollectionDocuments/Sv/nyheter/2013/500-1380-2013.pdf | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222034/http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/blekinge/SiteCollectionDocuments/Sv/nyheter/2013/500-1380-2013.pdf | archivedate = 2013-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Cited sources===\n*{{Cite book|title=Forgotten disease: illnesses transformed in Chinese medicine|last=HA Smith|year=2017|isbn=9781503603509|oclc=993877848|doi = 10.1093/jhmas/jry029}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Beriberi}}\n* {{cite book |author= |author-link = |chapter= BERI-BERI|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica; A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, Literature and General Information |pages= 774\u2013775 |year=1910 |volume= III (AUSTRIA LOWER to BISECTRIX )|edition= 11th |publisher=At the University Press |place=Cambridge, England and New York|chapter-url= https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabrit03chisrich/page/774 |accessdate= 23 October 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}\n* {{cite journal|title= British India and the beri-beri problem|journal = Medical History|volume = 54|issue = 3|pages = 295\u2013314|pmc = 2889456|year = 2010|author1 = ARNOLD D|pmid = 20592882|doi = 10.1017/S0025727300004622}}\n\n{{Medical resources\n|   DiseasesDB     = 14107\n|   ICD10          = {{ICD10|E|51}}\n|   ICD9           = {{ICD9|265.0}}\n|   ICDO           =\n|   OMIM           =\n|   MedlinePlus    = 000339\n|   eMedicineSubj  = ped\n|   eMedicineTopic = 229\n|   eMedicine_mult = {{eMedicine2|med|221}}\n|   MeshID         = D001602\n}}\n\n{{Nutritional pathology}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Reduplicants]]\n[[Category:Vitamin deficiencies]]\n[[Category:Thiamine]]\n[[Category:RTT]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Beri beri|the African ethnic group|Kanuri people}}\n{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Thiamine deficiency<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| synonyms        = Beriberi, vitamin B<sub>1</sub> deficiency, thiamine-deficiency syndrome<ref name=GARD2015/><ref name=Ad2017/>\n| image           = Beriberi USNLM.jpg\n| caption         = A person with beriberi during the early twentieth century in [[South-East Asia]]\n| field           = [[Neurology]], [[cardiology]], [[pediatrics]]\n| symptoms        = {{Unbulleted list|''Wet:'' Fast heart rate, shortness of breath, leg swelling<ref name=GARD2015/>|''Dry:'' Numbness, confusion, trouble moving the legs, pain<ref name=GARD2015/>}}\n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = Wet, dry, gastrointestinal<ref name=Fer2018/>\n| causes          = Not enough [[thiamine]]<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| risks           = Diet of mostly [[white rice]]; [[alcoholism]], [[dialysis]], chronic [[diarrhea]], [[diuretics]]<ref name=GARD2015/><ref name=CDC2012/>\n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = [[Food fortification]]<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| treatment       = [[Thiamine supplementation]]<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = Rare (US)<ref name=GARD2015/>\n| deaths          = \n}}\n<!-- Definition and symptoms -->\n'''Thiamine deficiency''' is a medical condition of low levels of [[thiamine]] (vitamin B<sub>1</sub>).<ref name=GARD2015/> A severe and chronic form is known as '''beriberi'''.<ref name=GARD2015>{{cite web|title=Beriberi|url=https://rarediseases.info.nih.gov/diseases/9948/beriberi|website=Genetic and Rare Diseases Information Center (GARD) \u2013 an NCATS Program|accessdate=11 November 2017|language=en|date=2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111205215/https://rarediseases.info.nih.gov/diseases/9948/beriberi|archivedate=11 November 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Hermann\">{{cite book|last1=Hermann|first1=Wolfgang|last2=Obeid|first2=Rima|title=Vitamins in the prevention of human diseases|date=2011|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|location=Berlin|isbn=9783110214482|page=58}}</ref> There are two main types in adults: wet beriberi, and dry beriberi.<ref name=GARD2015/> Wet beriberi affects the [[cardiovascular system]] resulting in a fast heart rate, [[shortness of breath]], and [[pedal edema|leg swelling]].<ref name=GARD2015/> Dry beriberi affects the [[nervous system]] resulting in [[peripheral neuropathy|numbness of the hands and feet]], confusion, trouble moving the legs, and pain.<ref name=GARD2015/> A form with loss of appetite and [[constipation]] may also occur.<ref name=Fer2018>{{cite book|last1=Ferri|first1=Fred F.|title=Ferri's Clinical Advisor 2018 E-Book: 5 Books in 1|date=2017|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9780323529570|page=1368|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=wGclDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1368|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111204713/https://books.google.ca/books?id=wGclDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA1368|archivedate=2017-11-11}}</ref> Another type, acute beriberi, is found mostly in babies and presents with loss of appetite, vomiting, [[lactic acidosis]], changes in heart rate, and enlargement of the heart.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gropper, Sareen S. and Smith, Jack L.|edition=6|title=Advanced Nutrition and Human Metabolism|year=2013|publisher=Wadsworth, Cengage Learning|isbn=978-1133104056|page=324}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Cause and diagnosis -->\nRisk factors include a diet of mostly [[white rice]], as well as [[alcoholism]], [[dialysis]], chronic [[diarrhea]], and taking high doses of [[diuretics]].<ref name=GARD2015/><ref name=CDC2012/> Rarely it may be due to a [[genetics|genetic]] condition that results in difficulties absorbing thiamine found in food.<ref name=GARD2015/> [[Wernicke encephalopathy]] and [[Korsakoff syndrome]] are forms of dry beriberi.<ref name=CDC2012>{{cite web|title=Nutrition and Growth Guidelines {{!}} Domestic Guidelines - Immigrant and Refugee Health|url=https://www.cdc.gov/immigrantrefugeehealth/guidelines/domestic/nutrition-growth.html|website=CDC|accessdate=11 November 2017|language=en-us|date=March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111205445/https://www.cdc.gov/immigrantrefugeehealth/guidelines/domestic/nutrition-growth.html|archivedate=11 November 2017}}</ref> Diagnosis is based on symptoms, low levels of thiamine in the urine, high blood [[lactic acid|lactate]], and improvement with treatment.<ref name=Sw2017>{{cite book|last1=Swaiman|first1=Kenneth F.|last2=Ashwal|first2=Stephen|last3=Ferriero|first3=Donna M.|last4=Schor|first4=Nina F.|last5=Finkel|first5=Richard S.|last6=Gropman|first6=Andrea L.|last7=Pearl|first7=Phillip L.|last8=Shevell|first8=Michael|title=Swaiman's Pediatric Neurology E-Book: Principles and Practice|date=2017|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=9780323374811|page=e929|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=PJ9tDgAAQBAJ&pg=SL5-PA929|language=en|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171111204954/https://books.google.ca/books?id=PJ9tDgAAQBAJ&pg=SL5-PA929|archivedate=2017-11-11}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Prevention and treatment -->\nTreatment is by [[thiamine supplementation]], either by mouth or by injection.<ref name=GARD2015/> With treatment, symptoms generally resolve in a couple of weeks.<ref name=Sw2017/> The disease may be prevented at the population level through the [[fortification of food]].<ref name=GARD2015/>\n\n<!-- Epidemiology and history -->\nThiamine deficiency is rare in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thiamin Fact Sheet for Consumers|url=https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Thiamin-Consumer/|publisher=Office of Dietary Supplements (ODS): USA.gov|accessdate=April 10, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029065129/https://ods.od.nih.gov/factsheets/Thiamin-Consumer/|archivedate=October 29, 2017}}</ref> It remains relatively common in [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref name=Ad2017>{{cite journal|last1=Adamolekun|first1=B|last2=Hiffler|first2=L|title=A diagnosis and treatment gap for thiamine deficiency disorders in sub-Saharan Africa?|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|volume=1408|issue=1|pages=15\u201319|date=24 October 2017|doi=10.1111/nyas.13509|pmid=29064578|bibcode=2017NYASA1408...15A|doi-access=free}}</ref> Outbreaks have been seen in [[refugee camps]].<ref name=CDC2012/> Thiamine deficiency has been described for thousands of years in Asia and became more common in the late 1800s with the increased processing of rice.<ref name=Lan2010>{{cite book|last1=Lanska|first1=DJ|title=Chapter 30: historical aspects of the major neurological vitamin deficiency disorders: the water-soluble B vitamins.|journal=Handbook of Clinical Neurology|date=2010|volume=95|pages=445\u201376|doi=10.1016/S0072-9752(08)02130-1|pmid=19892133|isbn=9780444520098}}</ref>\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\n===Beriberi===\nSymptoms of beriberi include weight loss, [[emotion]]al disturbances, impaired [[sensory perception]], [[muscle weakness|weakness]] and [[pain]] in the limbs, and periods of irregular [[heart rate]]. [[Edema]] (swelling of bodily tissues) is common. It may increase the amount of [[lactic acid]] and [[pyruvic acid]] within the blood. In advanced cases, the disease may cause [[high-output cardiac failure]] and death.\n\nSymptoms may occur concurrently with those of [[Wernicke's encephalopathy]], a primarily neurological thiamine-deficiency related condition.\n\nBeriberi is divided into four categories as follows. The first three are historical and the fourth, gastrointestinal beriberi, was recognized in 2004:\n*''Dry beriberi'' especially affects the peripheral nervous system.\n*''Wet beriberi'' especially affects the cardiovascular system and other bodily systems.\n*''Infantile beriberi'' affects the babies of malnourished mothers.\n*''Gastrointestinal beriberi'' affects the digestive system and other bodily systems.\n\n====Dry beriberi====\nDry beriberi causes wasting and partial [[paralysis]] resulting from damaged peripheral [[nerve]]s.  It is also referred to as endemic neuritis. It is characterized by:\n*Difficulty in walking\n*Tingling or loss of sensation ([[Paresthesia|numbness]]) in hands and feet \n*Loss of tendon reflexes<ref name=Katsura/>\n*Loss of muscle function or paralysis of the lower legs\n*Mental confusion/speech difficulties\n*Pain\n*Involuntary eye movements ([[Pathologic nystagmus|nystagmus]])\n*Vomiting\n\nA selective impairment of the large proprioceptive sensory fibers without motor impairment can occur and present as a prominent sensory [[ataxia]], which is a loss of balance and coordination due to loss of the proprioceptive inputs from the periphery and loss of position sense.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1038/nrneurol.2010.16 |title=Subacute sensory ataxia and optic neuropathy with thiamine deficiency|year=2010 |last1=Spinazzi |first1=Marco |last2=Angelini |first2=Corrado |last3=Patrini |first3=Cesare|journal=Nature Reviews Neurology |volume=6 |issue=5 |pages=288\u201393 |pmid=20308997}}</ref>\n\n===Brain disease===\n[[Wernicke's encephalopathy]] (WE), [[Korsakoff's syndrome]] (alcohol amnestic disorder), [[Wernicke\u2013Korsakoff syndrome]] are forms of dry beriberi.<ref name=CDC2012/>\n\nWernicke's encephalopathy is the most frequently encountered manifestation of thiamine deficiency in Western society,<ref name=\"Kril\">{{cite journal | author = Kril JJ | title = Neuropathology of thiamine deficiency disorders | journal = Metab Brain Dis | year = 1996 | volume = 11| issue=1 | pages=9\u201317 | doi = 10.1007/BF02080928 | pmid = 8815394}}</ref><ref>For an interesting discussion on thiamine fortification of foods, specifically targetting beer, see {{cite journal\n |journal     = Medical Journal of Australia\n |title       = Wernicke's encephalopathy and thiamine fortification of food: time for a new direction?\n |url         = http://www.mja.com.au/public/issues/jun1/drew/drew.html\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110831104941/http://www.mja.com.au/public/issues/jun1/drew/drew.html\n |archivedate = 2011-08-31\n}}</ref> though it may also occur in patients with impaired nutrition from other causes, such as gastrointestinal disease,<ref name=\"Kril\"/> those with [[HIV/AIDS]], and with the injudicious administration of [[route of administration#Local or systemic effect|parenteral]] glucose or [[hyperalimentation]] without adequate B-vitamin supplementation.<ref>{{cite journal  |vauthors=Butterworth RF, Gaudreau C, Vincelette J, etal | journal= Metab Brain Dis |year=1991 |volume=6 |pages=207\u201312 |doi=10.1007/BF00996920 |title=Thiamine deficiency and wernicke's encephalopathy in AIDS |pmid=1812394 |issue=4}}</ref> This is a striking neuro-psychiatric disorder characterized by paralysis of eye movements, abnormal stance and gait, and markedly deranged mental function.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Harper C. |title=Wernicke's encephalopathy, a more common disease than realised (a neuropathological study of 51 cases)|journal =J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry |year=1979|volume=42|pages=226\u2013231|doi=10.1136/jnnp.42.3.226|pmid=438830|issue=3|pmc=490724}}</ref>\n\n[[Korsakoff's syndrome]] is, in general, considered to occur with deterioration of brain function in patients initially diagnosed with WE.<ref>McCollum EV  ''A History of Nutrition''. Cambridge, MA: Riverside Press, Houghton Mifflin; 1957.</ref> This is an amnestic-confabulatory syndrome characterized by [[retrograde amnesia|retrograde]] and [[anterograde amnesia]], impairment of conceptual functions, and decreased spontaneity and initiative.<ref name=\"Butterworth RF. Thiamin 2006\">Butterworth RF. Thiamin. In: Shils ME, Shike M, Ross AC, Caballero B, Cousins RJ, editors. Modern Nutrition in Health and Disease, 10th ed. Baltimore: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; 2006.</ref>\n\nAlcoholics may have thiamine deficiency because of the following:\n* Inadequate nutritional intake:  Alcoholics tend to intake less than the recommended amount of thiamine.\n* Decreased uptake of thiamine from the GI tract:  Active transport of thiamine into enterocytes is disturbed during acute alcohol exposure.\n* Liver thiamine stores are reduced due to hepatic steatosis or fibrosis.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Butterworth RF | journal=Drug Alcohol Rev |year=1993|volume=12|pages=315\u201322|doi=10.1080/09595239300185371|title=Pathophysiologic mechanisms responsible for the reversible (thiamine-responsive) and irreversible (thiamine non-responsive) neurological symptoms of Wernicke's encephalopathy|pmid=16840290|issue=3}}</ref>\n* Impaired thiamine utilization:  Magnesium, which is required for the binding of thiamine to thiamine-using enzymes within the cell, is also deficient due to chronic alcohol consumption.  The inefficient utilization of any thiamine that does reach the cells will further exacerbate the thiamine deficiency.\n* Ethanol ''per se'' inhibits thiamine transport in the gastrointestinal system and blocks phosphorylation of thiamine to its cofactor form (ThDP).<ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Rindi G, Imarisio L, Patrini C |journal = Biochem Pharmacol | year = 1986 |volume=35 |pages=3903\u20138|doi=10.1016/0006-2952(86)90002-X|title=Effects of acute and chronic ethanol administration on regional thiamin pyrophosphokinase activity of the rat brain|pmid=3022743|issue=22}}</ref>\n\nFollowing improved nutrition and the removal of alcohol consumption, some impairments linked with thiamine deficiency are reversed, in particular poor brain functionality, although in more severe cases, Wernicke\u2013Korsakoff syndrome leaves permanent damage.  (See [[delirium tremens]].)\n\n===Wet beriberi===\nWet beriberi affects the [[heart]] and circulatory system. It is sometimes fatal, as it causes a combination of [[congestive heart failure|heart failure]] and weakening of the [[capillary]] walls, which causes the peripheral tissues to become edematous. Wet beriberi is characterized by:\n*Increased heart rate\n*[[Vasodilation]] leading to decreased systemic vascular resistance, and high output heart failure<ref>{{Cite journal | pmid = 11242561|doi=10.1007/s11936-001-0070-1| year = 2001| last1 = Anand| first1 = I. S.| title = High Output Cardiac Failure| journal = Current Treatment Options in Cardiovascular Medicine| volume = 3| issue = 2| pages = 151\u2013159| last2 = Florea| first2 = V. G.}}</ref>\n*Elevated [[jugular venous pressure]]<ref name=twomodes>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.3.5774.567 |title=Cardiac Beriberi: Two Modes of Presentation |year=1971 |last1=McIntyre |first1=Neil |last2=Stanley |first2=Nigel N. |journal=BMJ |volume=3 |issue=5774 |pages=567\u20139 |pmid=5571454 |pmc=1798841}}</ref>\n*Dyspnea (shortness of breath) on exertion\n*Paroxysmal nocturnal [[dyspnea]]\n*Peripheral [[oedema|edema]]<ref name=twomodes/> (swelling of lower legs)\n*[[Dilated cardiomyopathy]]\n\n===Gastrointestinal beriberi===\nGastrointestinal beriberi causes abdominal pain. Gastrointestinal beriberi is characterized by:\n*Abdominal pain\n*Nausea\n*Vomiting\n*Lactic acidosis<ref>{{cite journal | author = Donnino M | year = 2004 | title = Gastrointestinal Beriberi: A Previously Unrecognized Syndrome | url = | journal = Ann Intern Med | volume = 141 | issue = 11| pages = 898\u2013899 | doi = 10.7326/0003-4819-141-11-200412070-00035 | pmid = 15583247 }}</ref><ref>Duca, J., Lum, C., & Lo, A. (2015). Elevated Lactate Secondary to Gastrointestinal Beriberi. J GEN INTERN MED Journal of General Internal Medicine</ref>\n\n===Infants===\nInfantile beriberi usually occurs between two and six months of age in children whose mothers have inadequate thiamine intake. It may present as either wet or dry beriberi.<ref name=Ad2017/>\n\nIn the acute form, the baby develops [[dyspnea]] and [[cyanosis]] and soon dies of [[heart failure]]. These symptoms may be described in infantile beriberi:\n*Hoarseness, where the child makes moves to moan but emits no sound or just faint moans<ref name=latham>{{cite book | chapter-url = http://www.fao.org/docrep/006/w0073s/w0073s0k.htm | title = Human nutrition in the developing world (Food and Nutrition Series \u2013 No. 29) | chapter = Chapter 16. Beriberi and thiamine deficiency | first = Michael C. | last = Latham | publisher = Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) | issn = 1014-3181 | location = Rome | year = 1997 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140203001516/http://www.fao.org/docrep/006/w0073s/w0073s0k.htm | archivedate = 2014-02-03 }}</ref> caused by nerve paralysis<ref name=Katsura/>\n*Weight loss, becoming thinner and then [[marasmic]] as the disease progresses<ref name=latham/>\n*Vomiting<ref name=latham/>\n*Diarrhea<ref name=latham/>\n*Pale skin<ref name=Katsura>{{cite journal | url = http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_62_(chp9).pdf | first = E. | last = Katsura | first2 = T. | last2 = Oiso | title = Chapter 9. Beriberi | journal = World Health Organization Monograph Series No. 62: Nutrition in Preventive Medicine | editor-first = G.H. | editor-last = Beaton | editor2-first = J.M. | editor2-last = Bengoa | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva | year = 1976 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110708000808/http://whqlibdoc.who.int/monograph/WHO_MONO_62_(chp9).pdf | archivedate = 2011-07-08 }}</ref>\n*Edema<ref name=Katsura/><ref name=latham/>\n*Ill temper<ref name=Katsura/>\n*Alterations of the cardiovascular system, especially [[tachycardia]] (rapid heart rate)<ref name=Katsura/>\n*[[Convulsions]] occasionally observed in the terminal stages<ref name=latham/>\n\n==Cause==\nBeriberi may also be caused by shortcomings other than inadequate intake: [[digestive disease|diseases]] or operations on the digestive tract, [[alcoholism]],<ref name=twomodes/> [[dialysis]], [[genetic deficiencies]], etc. All these causes mainly affect the central nervous system, and provoke the development of what is known as [[Wernicke's encephalopathy|Wernicke's disease or Wernicke's encephalopathy]].\n\nWernicke's disease is one of the most prevalent neurological or neuropsychiatric diseases.<ref name=\"Cernicchiaro 2007\">{{citation| url = http://enfermedad-de-wernicke.weebly.com/| title = Enfermedad de Wernicke (o Encefalopat\u00eda de Wernicke). Monitoring an acute and recovered case for twelve years.| trans-title = Wernicke\u00b4s Disease (or Wernicke\u00b4s Encephalopathy)| first = Luis| last = Cernicchiaro| language = Spanish| year = 2007| url-status = live| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130522155106/http://enfermedad-de-wernicke.weebly.com/| archivedate = 2013-05-22}}</ref> In [[autopsy]] series, features of Wernicke lesions are observed in approximately 2% of general cases.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/794583-overview#a0156 | title = Wernicke Encephalopathy | first = Philip N | last = Salen | editor-first = Rick | editor-last = Kulkarni | website = Medscape | date = 1 March 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130512085230/http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/794583-overview#a0156 | archivedate = 12 May 2013 }}</ref> Medical record research shows that about 85% had not been diagnosed, although only 19% would be asymptomatic. In children, only 58% were diagnosed. In [[alcohol abuse]]rs, autopsy series showed neurological damages at rates of 12.5% or more. Mortality caused by Wernicke's disease reaches 17% of diseases, which means 3.4/1000 or about 25 million contemporaries.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Harper |first = CG | last2 = Giles |first2 = M |last3 = Finlay-Jones | first3= R | pmid = 3701343  | journal = J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry | date = April 1986 | volume = 49 | issue = 4 | pages = 341\u20135 | title = Clinical signs in the Wernicke-Korsakoff complex: a retrospective analysis of 131 cases diagnosed at necropsy | doi=10.1136/jnnp.49.4.341 | pmc=1028756}}</ref><ref name=Harper1979>{{cite journal | last = Harper |first = C | pmid = 438830 | journal = J Neurol Neurosurg Psychiatry | date = March 1979 | volume = 42 | issue = 3 | pages = 226\u201331 | title = Wernicke's encephalopathy: a more common disease than realised. A neuropathological study of 51 cases | doi=10.1136/jnnp.42.3.226 | pmc=490724}}</ref> The number of people with Wernicke's disease may be even higher, considering that early stages may have dysfunctions prior to the production of observable lesions at necropsy. In addition, uncounted numbers of people can experience fetal damage and subsequent diseases.\n\n===Genetics===\nGenetic diseases of thiamine transport are rare but serious. [[Thiamine responsive megaloblastic anemia]] (TRMA) with [[diabetes mellitus]] and [[sensorineural deafness]]<ref>{{cite journal | title =Thiamine Responsive Megaloblastic Anemia with severe diabetes mellitus and sensorineural deafness (TRMA) |pmid=249270 | year =1978 | last1 =Slater | first1 =PV | volume =7 | issue =11 | pages =40\u20133 | journal =The Australian Nurses' Journal}}</ref> is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by mutations in the gene [[SLC19A2]],<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 603941 |date=Dec 1977 |author1=Kopriva, V |author2=Bilkovic, R |author3=Licko, T | title = Tumours of the small intestine (author's transl) | volume = 31 | issue = 8 | pages = 549\u201353 | issn = 0009-0565 | journal = Ceskoslovenska Gastroenterologie a Vyziva}}</ref> a high affinity thiamine transporter. TRMA patients do not show signs of systemic thiamine deficiency, suggesting redundancy in the thiamine transport system. This has led to the discovery of a second high-affinity thiamine transporter, [[SLC19A3]].<ref>{{cite journal | pmid =606152 |date=Dec 1977 | author =Beissel, J | title =The role of right catheterization in valvular prosthesis surveillance (author's transl) | volume =26 | issue =6 | pages =587\u20139 | issn =0003-3928 | journal =Annales de Cardiologie et d'Ang\u00e9iologie}}</ref><ref>{{OMIM|249270}}</ref> [[Leigh disease]] (subacute necrotising encephalomyelopathy) is an inherited disorder that affects mostly infants in the first years of life and is invariably fatal. Pathological similarities between Leigh disease and WE led to the hypothesis that the cause was a defect in thiamine metabolism. One of the most consistent findings has been an abnormality of the activation of the [[pyruvate dehydrogenase]] complex.<ref>Butterworth RF. Pyruvate dehydrogenase deficiency disorders. In: McCandless DW, ed. ''Cerebral Energy Metabolism and Metabolic Encephalopathy''. Plenum Publishing Corp.; 1985.</ref>\n\nMutations in the [[SLC19A3]] gene have been linked to [[biotin-thiamine responsive basal ganglia disease]]<ref>[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK169615/ Biotin-Thiamine-Responsive Basal Ganglia Disease - GeneReviews\u00ae - NCBI Bookshelf<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509171903/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK169615/ |date=2018-05-09 }}</ref>, which is treated with pharmacological doses of thiamine and [[biotin]], another [[B vitamin]].\n\nOther disorders in which a putative role for thiamine has been implicated include [[subacute necrotising encephalomyelopathy]], [[opsoclonic cerebellopathy]] (a paraneoplastic syndrome), and [[Nigerian seasonal ataxia]]. In addition, several inherited disorders of ThDP-dependent enzymes have been reported,<ref>Blass JP. Inborn errors of pyruvate metabolism. In: Stanbury JB, Wyngaarden JB, Frederckson DS et al., eds. ''Metabolic Basis of Inherited Disease''. 5th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill, 1983.</ref> which may respond to thiamine treatment.<ref name=\"Butterworth RF. Thiamin 2006\"/>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\nThiamine in the human body has a half-life of 18 days and is quickly exhausted, particularly when metabolic demands exceed intake. A derivative of thiamine, [[thiamine pyrophosphate]] (TPP), is a cofactor involved in the [[citric acid cycle]], as well as connecting the [[Glycolysis|breakdown of sugars]] with the citric acid cycle. The citric acid cycle is a central metabolic pathway involved in the regulation of carbohydrate, lipid, and amino acid metabolism, and its disruption due to thiamine deficiency inhibits the production of many molecules including the neurotransmitters [[glutamic acid]] and [[GABA]].<ref name=Sechi>{{cite journal|last=Sechi|first=G|last2=Serra |first2=A |title=Wernicke's encephalopathy: new clinical settings and recent advances in diagnosis and management|journal=Lancet Neurology|date=May 2007 | volume=6 | issue=5 | pages=442\u201355 | pmid=17434099 |doi=10.1016/S1474-4422(07)70104-7 }}</ref> Additionally thiamine may also be directly involved in [[Neuromodulation (biology)|neuromodulation]].<ref name=Hirsch>{{cite journal|last=Hirsch |first=JA| last2=Parrott |first2=J |title=New considerations on the neuromodulatory role of thiamine |journal=Pharmacology |date=2012| volume=89 | issue=1\u20132 | pages=111\u20136 | pmid=22398704 |doi=10.1159/000336339 }}</ref>\n\n==Diagnosis==\n[[File:Thiochromes.jpg|thumb|Oxidation of thiamine derivatives to fluorescent thiochromes by potassium ferricyanide under alkaline conditions]]\n\nA positive diagnosis test for thiamine deficiency involves measuring the activity of the enzyme [[transketolase]] in [[erythrocyte]]s (Erythrocyte transketolase activation assay). Alternatively, thiamine and its phosphphosphorylated derivatives, can directly be detected in whole blood, tissues, foods, animal feed, and pharmaceutical preparations following the conversion of thiamine to [[fluorescent]] thiochrome derivatives (Thiochrome assay) and separation by [[high-performance liquid chromatography]] (HPLC).<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0003-2697(91)90505-N | last1 = Bettendorff | first1 = L | last2 = Peeters | first2 = M. | last3 = Jouan | first3 = C. | last4 = Wins | first4 = P. | last5 = Schoffeniels | first5 = E. |name-list-format=vanc | year = 1991 | title = Determination of thiamin and its phosphate esters in cultured neurons and astrocytes using an ion-pair reversed-phase high-performance liquid chromatographic method | url = | journal = Anal. Biochem. | volume = 198 | issue = 1| pages = 52\u201359 | pmid = 1789432 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/j.jpba.2004.08.038 | last1 = Losa | first1 = R | last2 = Sierra | first2 = MI | last3 = Fern\u00e1ndez | first3 = A | last4 = Blanco | first4 = D | last5 = Buesa | first5 = JM. |name-list-format=vanc | year = 2005 | title = Determination of thiamine and its phosphorylated forms in human plasma, erythrocytes and urine by HPLC and fluorescence detection: a preliminary study on cancer patients | url = | journal = J Pharm Biomed Anal | volume = 37 | issue = 5| pages = 1025\u20131029 | pmid = 15862682 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1373/clinchem.2007.099077 | last1 = Lu | first1 = J | last2 = Frank | first2 = EL. |name-list-format=vanc |date=May 2008 | title = Rapid HPLC measurement of thiamine and its phosphate esters in whole blood | url = | journal = Clin. Chem. | volume = 54 | issue = 5| pages = 901\u2013906 | pmid = 18356241 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Capillary electrophoresis (CE) techniques and in-capillary enzyme reaction methods have emerged as alternative techniques in quantifying and monitoring thiamine levels in samples.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Shabangi | first1 = M | last2 = Sutton | first2 = JA. |name-list-format=vanc | year = 2005 | title = Separation of thiamin and its phosphate esters by capillary zone electrophoresis and its application to the analysis of water-soluble vitamins | url = | journal = Journal of Pharmaceutical and Biomedical Analysis | volume = 38 | issue = 1| pages = 66\u201371 | pmid = 15907621 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpba.2004.11.061 }}</ref>\nThe normal thiamine concentration in EDTA-blood is about 20-100&nbsp;\u00b5g/l.\n\n==Treatment==\nMany people with beriberi can be treated with thiamine alone.<ref>Nguyen-Khoa, Dieu-Thu  [http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/116930-treatment Beriberi (Thiamine Deficiency) Treatment & Management] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140324014710/http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/116930-treatment |date=2014-03-24 }}. Mescape</ref> Given thiamine intravenously (and later orally), rapid and dramatic <ref name=twomodes/> recovery can occur within hours. If concentrated thiamine supplements are not available, thiamine-rich diets (e.g. [[whole wheat bread|whole grain brown bread]]) will lead to recovery, though at a much slower rate.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nFollowing thiamine treatment, rapid improvement occurs, in general, within 24 hours.<ref name=\"Tanphaichitr\">Tanphaichitr V. Thiamin. In: Shils ME, Olsen JA, Shike M et al., editors. ''Modern Nutrition in Health and Disease''. 9th ed. Baltimore: Lippincott Williams & Wilkins; 1999</ref> Improvements of peripheral neuropathy may require several months of thiamine treatment.<ref>Maurice V, Adams RD, Collins GH. ''The Wernicke-Korsakoff Syndrome and Related Neurologic Disorders Due to Alcoholism and Malnutrition''. 2nd ed. Philadelphia: FA Davis, 1989.</ref>\n\n==Epidemiology==\nHistorically, beriberi was associated with a diet based on polished rice ([[white rice]]). When the relationship between the polishing of rice and the disease became clear, the deficiency could be treated and prevented by including inexpensive rice [[bran]] in the diet, among other things. Beriberi caused by inadequate nutritional intake of thiamine is rare today in developed countries{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} because of quality of food and the fact that many foods are fortified with vitamins.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} There are generally no reliable statistics for beriberi in developed or developing countries prior to the 20th century.{{Citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n\nBeriberi is a recurrent nutritional disease in detention houses, even in this century. In 1999, an outbreak of beriberi occurred in a detention center in Taiwan.<ref>{{Cite journal|year=2003|title=Outbreak of beriberi among illegal mainland Chinese immigrants at a detention center in Taiwan|journal=Public Health Rep|volume=118|issue=1|pages=59\u201364|doi=10.1093/phr/118.1.59|pmid=12604765|vauthors=Chen KT, Twu SJ, Chiou ST, Pan WH, Chang HJ, Serdula MK|pmc=1497506}}</ref> High rates of illness and death in overcrowded Haitian jails in 2007 were traced to the traditional practice of washing rice before cooking.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2007/01/haiti-mysterious-prison-ailment-traced-to-us-rice/ |title=Haiti: Mysterious Prison Ailment Traced to U.S. Rice |first1=Jeb |last1=Sprague |first2=Eunida |last2=Alexandra |agency=Inter Press Service |date=17 January 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130530034501/http://www.ipsnews.net/2007/01/haiti-mysterious-prison-ailment-traced-to-us-rice/ |archivedate=30 May 2013 }}</ref> In the [[Ivory Coast]], among a group of prisoners with heavy punishment, 64% were affected by beriberi. Before beginning treatment, prisoners exhibited symptoms of dry or wet beriberi with neurological signs (tingling: 41%), cardiovascular signs (dyspnoea: 42%, thoracic pain: 35%), and [[edema]]s of the lower limbs (51%). With treatment the rate of healing was about 97%.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1007/s13149-011-0136-6| pmid = 21336653| title = Le b\u00e9rib\u00e9ri, maladie nutritionnelle r\u00e9currente en milieu carc\u00e9ral en C\u00f4te-d'Ivoire| journal = Bulletin de la Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 de Pathologie Exotique| volume = 104| issue = 5| pages = 347\u2013351| year = 2011| last1 = Ak\u00e9-Tano | first1 = O.| last2 = Konan | first2 = E. Y.| last3 = Tetchi | first3 = E. O.| last4 = Ekou | first4 = F. K.| last5 = Ekra | first5 = D.| last6 = Coulibaly | first6 = A.| last7 = Dagnan | first7 = N. S.}}</ref>\n\nPopulations under extreme stress may be at higher risk for beriberi. [[Forced displacement|Displaced populations]], such as [[refugee]]s from war, are susceptible to micronutritional deficiency, including beriberi.<ref name=prinzo2009>{{cite journal |doi=10.1079/PNS2002151 |title=Meeting the challenges of micronutrient deficiencies in emergency-affected populations |year=2009 |last1=Prinzo |first1=Z. Weise |last2=de Benoist |first2=B. |journal=Proceedings of the Nutrition Society |volume=61 |issue=2 |pmid=12133207 |url=http://www.who.int/nutrition/publications/micronutrients/PNSvol61no2may02.pdf |pages=251\u20137 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019151311/http://www.who.int/nutrition/publications/micronutrients/PNSvol61no2may02.pdf |archivedate=2012-10-19 }}</ref> The severe nutritional deprivation caused by [[famine]] also can cause beriberis, although symptoms may be overlooked in clinical assessment or masked by other famine-related problems.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://fex.ennonline.net/1/diagnosing.aspx |title=Diagnosing Beriberi in Emergency Situations |first1=Mike |last1=Golden |journal=Field Exchange |date=May 1997 |issue=1 |page=18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019200706/http://fex.ennonline.net/1/diagnosing.aspx |archivedate=2012-10-19 }}</ref> An extreme weight-loss [[Dieting|diet]] can, rarely, induce a famine-like state and the accompanying beriberi.<ref name=twomodes/>\n\n==History==\nEarliest written descriptions of thiamine deficiency are from Ancient China in the context of [[chinese medicine]]. One of the earliest is by [[Ge Hong]] in his book ''Zhou hou bei ji fang'' (Emergency Formulas to Keep up Your Sleeve) written sometime during the [[3rd century]]. Hong called the illness by the name ''jiao qi'', which can be interpreted as \"foot [[qi]]\". He described the symptoms to include swelling, weakness and numbness of the feet. He also acknowledged that the illness could be deadly, and claimed that it could be cured by eating certain foods such as fermented soybeans in wine. Better known examples of early descriptions of \"foot qi\" are by [[Chao Yuanfang]] (who lived during 550\u2013630) in his book ''Zhu bing yuan hou lun'' (Sources and Symptoms of All Diseases)<ref name=\":0\">HA Smith, p. 26-28</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Benedict|first=CA|date=2018-10-25|title=Forgotten Disease: Illnesses Transformed in Chinese Medicine by Hilary A. Smith (review)|journal=Bulletin of the History of Medicine|volume=92|issue=3|pages=550\u2013551|doi=10.1353/bhm.2018.0059|issn=1086-3176}}</ref> and by [[Sun Simiao]] (581\u2013682) in his book ''Bei ji qian jin yao fang'' (Essential Emergency Formulas Worth a Thousand in Gold).<ref>HA Smith, p. 44</ref><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shen-nong.com/eng/history/suitang.html|title=TCM history V the Sui & Tang Dynasties|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714124755/http://www.shen-nong.com/eng/history/suitang.html|archivedate=2017-07-14|url-status=live|accessdate=2017-07-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itmonline.org/arts/sunsimiao.htm|title=Sun Simiao: Author of the Earliest Chinese Encyclopedia for Clinical Practice|accessdate=2007-06-15 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704150247/http://www.itmonline.org/arts/sunsimiao.htm |archivedate=2007-07-04}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 19th century, beriberi was studied by [[Takaki Kanehiro]], a British-trained Japanese medical doctor of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]].<ref name=Takaki>{{cite journal |first1=Yoshinori |last1=Itokawa |year=1976 |title=Kanehiro Takaki (1849\u20131920): A Biographical Sketch |journal=Journal of Nutrition |pmid=772183 |volume=106 |issue=5 |pages=581\u20138|doi=10.1093/jn/106.5.581 }}</ref> Beriberi was a serious problem in the Japanese navy: Sailors fell ill an average of four times a year in the period 1878 to 1881, and 35% were cases of beriberi.<ref name=Takaki/> In 1883, Takaki learned of a very high incidence of beriberi among cadets on a training mission from Japan to Hawaii, via New Zealand and South America. The voyage lasted more than nine months and resulted in 169 cases of sickness and 25 deaths on a ship of 376 men. With the support of the Japanese Navy, he conducted an experiment in which another ship was deployed on the same route, except that its crew was fed a diet of meat, fish, barley, rice, and beans. At the end of the voyage, this crew had only 14 cases of beriberi and no deaths. This convinced Takaki and the Japanese Navy that diet was the cause.<ref name=Takaki/> In 1884, Takaki observed that beriberi was common among low-ranking crew who were often provided free rice and thus ate little else, but not among crews of Western navies, nor among Japanese officers who consumed a more varied diet.\n\nIn 1897, [[Christiaan Eijkman]], a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] [[physician]] and [[pathologist]], demonstrated that beriberi is caused by poor diet, and discovered that feeding unpolished rice (instead of the polished variety) to chickens helped to prevent beriberi. The following year, Sir [[Frederick Hopkins]] postulated that some foods contained \"accessory factors\"\u2014in addition to proteins, carbohydrates, fats, and salt\u2014that were necessary for the functions of the human body.<ref name=\"Challem\">{{cite web | first = Jack | last = Challem | year = 1997 | url = http://www.thenutritionreporter.com/history_of_vitamins.html | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100608223713/http://www.thenutritionreporter.com/history_of_vitamins.html | archivedate = 8 June 2010 | title = The Past, Present and Future of Vitamins}}{{MEDRS|date=July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation | url = http://nobelprize.org/educational_games/medicine/vitamin_b1/eijkman.html | title = Christiaan Eijkman, Beriberi and Vitamin B1 | publisher = Nobelprize.org, Nobel Media AB | accessdate = 8 July 2013 | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100117191212/http://nobelprize.org/educational_games/medicine/vitamin_b1/eijkman.html | archivedate = 17 January 2010 }}</ref> In 1901, [[Gerrit Grijns]], a Dutch physician and assistant to [[Christiaan Eijkman]] in the Netherlands, correctly interpreted beriberi as a deficiency syndrome,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Grijns |first1=G. |year=1901 |title=Over polyneuritis gallinarum |journal=Geneeskundig Tijdschrift voor Nederlandsch-Indie |volume=43 |pages=3\u2013110}}</ref> and between 1910 and 1913, [[Edward Bright Vedder]] established that an extract of [[rice bran]] is a treatment for beriberi.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} In 1929, Eijkman and Hopkins were awarded the [[Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine]] for their discoveries.\n\n===Etymology===\nAlthough according to the [[Oxford English Dictionary]], the term \"beriberi\" comes from a [[Sinhala language|Sinhalese]] phrase meaning \"weak, weak\" or \"I cannot, I cannot\", the word being [[reduplication|duplicated]] for emphasis,<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]: \"Beri-beri&nbsp;... a Cingalese word, f. ''beri'' weakness, the reduplication being intensive&nbsp;...\", page 203, 1937</ref> the origin of the phrase is questionable. It has also been suggested to come from Hindi, Arabic and a few other languages, with many meanings like \"weakness\", \"sailor\" and even \"sheep\". Such suggested origins were listed by [[Heinrich Botho Scheube]] among others. [[Edward Vedder]] wrote in his book ''Beriberi'' (1913) that \"it is impossible to definitely trace the origin of the word beriberi\". Word ''berbere'' was used in writing at least as early as 1568 by [[Diogo do Couto]], when he described the deficiency in India.<ref>HA Smith, p. 118-119</ref>\n\n\"Kakke\", which is a Japanese synonym for thiamine deficiency, comes from the way \"jiao qi\" is pronounced in Japanese.<ref name=\":2\">HA Smith, p. 149</ref> \"Jiao qi\" is an old word used in Chinese medicine to describe beriberi.<ref name=\":0\" /> \"Kakke\" is supposed to have entered into the Japanese language sometime between the 6th and 8th centuries.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Other animals==\n\n===Poultry===\nAs most feedstuffs used in poultry diets contain enough quantities of vitamins to meet the requirements in this species, deficiencies in this vitamin do not occur with commercial diets. This was, at least, the opinion in the 1960s.<ref>''Merck Veterinary Manual'', ed 1967, pp 1440-1441.</ref>\n\nMature chickens show signs three weeks after being fed a deficient diet. In young chicks, it can appear before two weeks of age.\n\nOnset is sudden in young chicks. There is anorexia and an unsteady gait. Later on, there are locomotor signs, beginning with an apparent paralysis of the flexor of the toes. The characteristic position is called \"stargazing\", meaning a chick \"sitting on its hocks and the head in [[opisthotonos]]\".\n\nResponse to administration of the vitamin is rather quick, occurring a few hours later.<ref>R.E. Austic and M.L. Scott, Nutritional deficiency diseases, in ''Diseases of poultry'', ed. by M.S. Hofstad, Iowa State University Press, Ames, Iowa, USA {{ISBN|0-8138-0430-2}}, p. 50.</ref><ref>The disease is described more carefully here: [http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/206934.htm merckvetmanual.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081222050129/http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm%2Fbc%2F206934.htm |date=2008-12-22 }}</ref>\n\nDifferential diagnosis include [[riboflavin deficiency]] and [[avian encephalomyelitis]]. In riboflavin deficiency, the \"curled toes\" is a characteristic symptom. Muscle tremor is typical of avian encephalomyelitis. A therapeutic [[medical diagnosis|diagnosis]] can be tried by supplementing thiamine only in the affected bird. If the animals do not respond in a few hours, thiamine deficiency can be excluded.\n\n===Ruminants===\n[[Polioencephalomalacia]] (PEM) is the most common thiamine deficiency disorder in young ruminant and nonruminant animals.  Symptoms of PEM include a profuse, but transient, diarrhea, listlessness, circling movements, star gazing or opisthotonus (head drawn back over neck), and muscle tremors.<ref>National Research Council. 1996. ''Nutrient Requirements of Beef Cattle'', Seventh Revised Ed. Washington, D.C.: National Academy Press.</ref>  The most common cause is high-carbohydrate feeds, leading to the overgrowth of thiaminase-producing bacteria, but dietary ingestion of thiaminase (e.g., in [[bracken]] fern), or inhibition of thiamine absorption by high sulfur intake are also possible.<ref>[http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm/bc/102000.htm Polioencephalomalacia: Introduction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233122/http://www.merckvetmanual.com/mvm/index.jsp?cfile=htm%2Fbc%2F102000.htm |date=2016-03-03 }}, ''Merck Veterinary Manual''</ref>  Another cause of PEM is ''Clostridium sporogenes'' or ''Bacillus aneurinolyticus'' infection. These bacteria produce [[thiaminase]]s that will cause an acute thiamine deficiency in the affected animal.<ref>[http://www.aces.edu/pubs/docs/U/UNP-0065/ Polioencephalomacia: Introduction] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528043219/http://www.aces.edu/pubs/docs/U/UNP-0065/ |date=2010-05-28 }}, \"ACES Publications\"</ref>\n\n===Snakes===\nSnakes that consume a diet largely composed of goldfish and feeder minnows are susceptible to developing thiamine deficiency. This is often a problem observed in captivity when keeping garter and ribbon snakes that are fed a goldfish-exclusive diet, as these fish contain thiaminase, an enzyme that breaks down thiamine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264981292 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-09-13 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913231717/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/264981292_Update_on_Common_Nutritional_Disorders_of_Captive_Reptiles |archivedate=2017-09-13 }}</ref>\n\n===Wild birds and fish===\nThiamine deficiency has been identified as the cause of a paralytic disease affecting wild birds in the Baltic Sea area dating back to 1982.<ref name=\"Balk\">{{cite journal | last1 = Balk | first1 = L | last2 = H\u00e4gerroth | first2 = PA | last3 = Akerman | first3 = G | last4 = Hanson | first4 = M | last5 = Tj\u00e4rnlund | first5 = U | last6 = Hansson | first6 = T | last7 = Hallgrimsson | first7 = GT | last8 = Zeb\u00fchr | first8 = Y | last9 = Broman | first9 = D | year = 2009 | title = Wild birds of declining European species are dying from a thiamine deficiency syndrome | url = | journal = Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A | volume = 106 | issue = 29| pages = 12001\u201312006 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.0902903106 | pmc = 2715476 | pmid = 19597145 | last10 = M\u00f6rner | first10 = T. | last11 = Sundberg | first11 = H. |display-authors=etal| bibcode = 2009PNAS..10612001B }}</ref> In this condition, there is difficulty in keeping the wings folded along the side of the body when resting, loss of the ability to fly and voice, with eventual paralysis of the wings and legs and death. It affects primarily 0.5\u20131&nbsp;kg sized birds such as the [[European herring gull|herring gull]] (''Larus argentatus''), [[common starling]] (''Sturnus vulgaris'') and [[common eider]] (''Somateria mollissima''). Researches noted, \"Because the investigated species occupy a wide range of ecological niches and positions in the food web, we are open to the possibility that other animal classes may suffer from thiamine deficiency as well.\"<ref name=\"Balk\"/><sup>p.&nbsp;12006</sup>\n\nIn the counties of [[Blekinge]] and [[Sk\u00e5ne]] (southernmost [[Sweden]]), mass deaths of several bird species, especially the [[European herring gull]], have been observed since the early 2000s. More recently, species of other classes seems to be affected. High mortality of [[Atlantic Salmon|salmon]] (''Salmo salar'') in the river [[M\u00f6rrums\u00e5n]] is reported, and mammals such as the [[Moose|Eurasian Elk]] (''Alces alces'') have died in unusually high numbers. Lack of thiamine is the common denominator where analysis is done. In April 2012, the County Administrative Board of Blekinge found the situation so alarming that they asked the Swedish government to set up a closer investigation.<ref name=\"L\u00e4nsstyrelsen Blekinge l\u00e4n\">{{cite journal | last1 = Blekinge l\u00e4n | first1 = L\u00e4nsstyrelsen | year = 2013 | title = 2012-04-15 500-1380-13 F\u00f6rh\u00f6jd d\u00f6dlighet hos f\u00e5gel, lax og \u00e4lg | url = http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/blekinge/SiteCollectionDocuments/Sv/nyheter/2013/500-1380-2013.pdf | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131202222034/http://www.lansstyrelsen.se/blekinge/SiteCollectionDocuments/Sv/nyheter/2013/500-1380-2013.pdf | archivedate = 2013-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Cited sources===\n*{{Cite book|title=Forgotten disease: illnesses transformed in Chinese medicine|last=HA Smith|year=2017|isbn=9781503603509|oclc=993877848|doi = 10.1093/jhmas/jry029}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Beriberi}}\n* {{cite book |author= |author-link = |chapter= BERI-BERI|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica; A Dictionary of Arts, Sciences, Literature and General Information |pages= 774\u2013775 |year=1910 |volume= III (AUSTRIA LOWER to BISECTRIX )|edition= 11th |publisher=At the University Press |place=Cambridge, England and New York|chapter-url= https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabrit03chisrich/page/774 |accessdate= 23 October 2018 |via= Internet Archive}}\n* {